"""
MKT Christ-in-Every-Verse Commentary — Genesis chapters 25–26
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-genesis-25-26.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/genesis.json (verse inventory)
- data/translation/draft/mediating/genesis.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/genesis.json (existing; merge_comm skips present entries)

Key Christological decisions:
- Gen 25:5 — Isaac as sole heir of Abraham is the type of Christ as heir of all things
  (Heb 1:2); Keturah's sons sent away is the narrowing of the covenant to the one seed.
- Gen 25:21 — Isaac's prayer for barren Rebekah is the climax of the barren-womb
  sequence that culminates in the virgin birth of Christ; nothing is impossible with God.
- Gen 25:23 — Paul's Rom 9:10-12 election text; before good or bad, God called — Christ
  as the chosen cornerstone elected before the foundation of the world (1 Pet 1:20; 2:6).
- Gen 25:26 — Jacob's heel-grasping refers back to Gen 3:15 (enmity/heel) and forward
  to the ongoing conflict Christ resolves; Hosea 12:3 connects Jacob's wrestling to his
  nature from the womb.
- Gen 25:34 — Heb 12:16 uses Esau selling his birthright as the NT type of trading
  covenant inheritance for momentary earthly satisfaction; opposite of Matt 13:44-46.
- Gen 26:4 — Paul cites "through your offspring all nations will be blessed" in Gal 3:8
  as the gospel proclaimed in advance (same promise as Gen 22:18, now to Isaac).
- Gen 26:12 — "hundredfold" yield echoes the parable of the sower (Matt 13:8).
- Gen 26:18-22 — Isaac's three wells (Esek/Sitnah/Rehoboth) form a patience-to-peace
  arc; Isaac's peacemaking by yielding is a type of Christ "our peace" (Eph 2:14).
- Gen 26:24 — "I am... do not be afraid" divine self-declaration is the formula Christ
  takes up in the Gospels (John 8:58; Matt 14:27).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {
"25": {
"1": "<p>Abraham had taken another wife, whose name was Keturah &#8212; the mention of Abraham&#8217;s second wife (or concubine; cf. 1 Chron 1:32) and her sons is the genealogical prologue that situates Isaac as the singular covenant heir among many natural sons. Abraham&#8217;s extensive family through Keturah demonstrates that the covenant narrowing to Isaac is not from lack of other options but from divine election. Paul&#8217;s argument in Rom 9:6&#8211;13 is precisely this: not all of Abraham&#8217;s descendants are the heirs of the promise. The covenant-heir is determined by God&#8217;s call, not by birth order or number &#8212; the logic that leads to Christ as the one seed through whom all Abraham&#8217;s true offspring inherit (Gal 3:16, 29).</p>",
"2": "<p>Keturah bore Abraham Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, Midian, Ishbak and Shuah &#8212; of these, Midian is the most significant canonically. Moses flees to Midian (Exod 2:15), marries Zipporah the Midianite, and encounters God at the burning bush in Midian (Exod 3:1). The Midianites later become a source of apostasy for Israel (Num 25:6; 31:1&#8211;18) and oppression (Judg 6&#8211;8). The Midianite connection &#8212; through Abraham&#8217;s secondary family &#8212; is a reminder that God works in and through even the non-covenant lines to accomplish his purposes (as with Jethro, Moses&#8217;s father-in-law, a Midianite priest who worships the LORD rightly in Exod 18:10&#8211;12).</p>",
"3": "<p>Jokshan was the father of Sheba and Dedan &#8212; the sons of Jokshan trace to the Arabian peninsula. Sheba appears in the OT as the land from which the Queen of Sheba travels to visit Solomon (1 Kgs 10:1&#8211;13). Jesus uses this visit as a type of the Gentile response to divine wisdom: &#8220;The Queen of the South will rise at the judgment with this generation and condemn it; for she came from the ends of the earth to listen to Solomon&#8217;s wisdom, and now something greater than Solomon is here&#8221; (Matt 12:42). The Sheba connection, traced through Abraham&#8217;s secondary family, is a canonical-context note on the far-reaching scope of Abraham&#8217;s genealogical influence.</p>",
"4": "<p>The sons of Midian were Ephah, Epher, Hanok, Abida and Eldaah &#8212; Isaiah 60:6 mentions the Midianites (Ephah specifically) among the nations who will bring gold and incense to honor the LORD at the time of Israel&#8217;s eschatological restoration: &#8220;Herds of camels will cover your land, young camels of Midian and Ephah.&#8221; The Magi who bring gold and frankincense to the infant Jesus (Matt 2:11) fulfill this vision. The Midianite offspring of Abraham become, in Isaiah&#8217;s vision, part of the Gentile procession to the restored Jerusalem &#8212; which the Magi&#8217;s visit anticipates. Abraham&#8217;s secondary offspring are within the scope of the eschatological gathering.</p>",
"5": "<p>Abraham left everything he owned to Isaac &#8212; the sole heirship of Isaac over all Abraham&#8217;s estate is the clearest legal statement of the covenant&#8217;s singular channel. The NT applies the same singular-heir logic to Christ: &#8220;in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son, whom he appointed heir of all things&#8221; (Heb 1:2). Christ is the Isaac who inherits everything; believers are &#8220;co-heirs with Christ&#8221; (Rom 8:17) &#8212; they inherit by virtue of their union with the one heir, not by independent right. The entire Abrahamic estate passed to Isaac; the entire divine inheritance is held by Christ and shared with those who are in him.</p>",
"6": "<p>While still living, Abraham gave gifts to the sons of his concubines and sent them east, away from his son Isaac &#8212; the separation of the non-heir sons from the heir echoes the Ishmael expulsion (21:14) and anticipates the final separation between those who inherit and those who do not. The gifts given before sending away correspond to God&#8217;s common grace: &#8220;he causes his sun to rise on the evil and the good&#8221; (Matt 5:45). The gifts are genuine; the separation is real. Both aspects &#8212; common blessing to all, particular covenant inheritance to the elect &#8212; find their ultimate expression in Christ through whom the world receives common grace and those who believe receive particular redemption (John 3:16&#8211;17).</p>",
"7": "<p>Abraham lived a hundred and seventy-five years &#8212; the length of Abraham&#8217;s life, full of covenant faithfulness (Heb 11:8&#8211;12). The lifespan functions as a measure of covenantal blessedness: Abraham promised a peaceful death at good old age (15:15) and receives it. The patriarchal longevity is the OT sign of blessing; Christ transforms the sign: &#8220;Whoever lives by believing in me will never die&#8221; (John 11:26). The covenant that Abraham trusted promised long life; the covenant Christ establishes promises eternal life &#8212; the antitype infinitely exceeds the type.</p>",
"8": "<p>Abraham breathed his last and died at a good old age, an old man and full of years; and he was gathered to his people &#8212; &#8220;gathered to his people&#8221; implies a corporate afterlife: the dead patriarch joins those who went before. Jesus cites this language in the resurrection debate: &#8220;God is not the God of the dead, but of the living&#8221; (Matt 22:32), concluding that Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob are alive before God. Christ&#8217;s resurrection confirms what &#8220;gathered to his people&#8221; assumed: the patriarchs are alive in the presence of God, awaiting the resurrection of the body. The death of Abraham is not the end of Abraham; the one who &#8220;believed God&#8221; (15:6) is alive with the God he trusted.</p>",
"9": "<p>Isaac and Ishmael buried Abraham in the cave of Machpelah &#8212; the two sons, covenant and non-covenant, united at their father&#8217;s burial. The reunion of the two estranged brothers at their father&#8217;s grave prefigures the eschatological gathering of all Abraham&#8217;s physical and spiritual children at the resurrection. Christ&#8217;s mission to reconcile: &#8220;he will gather together in one the scattered children of God&#8221; (John 11:52); &#8220;God was pleased&#8230; through him to reconcile to himself all things&#8221; (Col 1:19&#8211;20). The estrangement that the covenant lines produce in history is overcome at the end; the joint burial at Machpelah is a small anticipation of the final gathering under Christ.</p>",
"10": "<p>The field that Abraham had bought from the Hittites &#8212; there Abraham was buried with his wife Sarah &#8212; the covenant landholding (ch23) now serves its purpose: it receives the covenant patriarch in death. The burial in the promised land is the final covenant act of faith, planting the dead in the soil of the promise. Heb 11:13 says they &#8220;admitted that they were foreigners and strangers on earth&#8221; &#8212; but they buried their dead in the promised land rather than returning to Ur, staking their covenant claim. Christ&#8217;s burial in Joseph&#8217;s tomb in Jerusalem similarly plants his body in the promised city &#8212; from which the resurrection breaks forth. The dead planted in the promise do not stay buried.</p>",
"11": "<p>After Abraham&#8217;s death, God blessed his son Isaac, who then lived near Beer Lahai Roi &#8212; the covenant blessing passes immediately and completely from Abraham to Isaac. God does not pause or reconsider; the promise does not falter at the generational transition. The uninterrupted transmission of the covenant blessing is the assurance of the gospel&#8217;s permanence: &#8220;Jesus Christ is the same yesterday and today and forever&#8221; (Heb 13:8). The covenant does not depend on any individual patriarch&#8217;s life; it rests in the faithfulness of God who transfers it without loss. Beer Lahai Roi &#8212; the &#8220;well of the living one who sees me&#8221; (16:14) &#8212; is where Isaac lives, the site of God&#8217;s care for Hagar; God&#8217;s seeing encompasses Isaac too.</p>",
"12": "<p>This is the account of the family line of Abraham&#8217;s son Ishmael, whom Sarah&#8217;s slave, Hagar the Egyptian, bore to Abraham &#8212; the toledoth (account/genealogy) of Ishmael is placed before the Isaac narrative (v19) to close out the Ishmael line before the covenant story continues. The ordering demonstrates that Ishmael&#8217;s line, though real and significant, is not the covenant channel. Paul&#8217;s allegory (Gal 4:22&#8211;31) uses precisely this narrative structure: the Hagar/Ishmael line is the &#8220;according to the flesh&#8221; line that does not receive the inheritance; the Sarah/Isaac line is the &#8220;according to the promise&#8221; line that does. The genealogical positioning of Ishmael before Isaac signals the closing-off of one line and the continuation of the other.</p>",
"13": "<p>The sons of Ishmael: Nebaioth the firstborn, Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam &#8212; the twelve sons of Ishmael parallel the twelve sons of Jacob (35:22&#8211;26); both men have twelve sons who become twelve tribes or rulers. The twelve-tribe structure runs from Ishmael (twelve rulers, v16) through Jacob (twelve tribes) to the twelve apostles (Matt 10:2&#8211;4), who are the new leadership of the reconstituted covenant people under Christ. Christ appoints twelve &#8220;that they might be with him&#8221; (Mark 3:14), reconstituting the twelve-tribe structure of Israel in his new community.</p>",
"14": "<p>Mishma, Dumah, Massa &#8212; the Ishmael genealogy continues. Dumah appears in Isa 21:11 as the oracle against Edom; Massa appears in Prov 30:1 (the words of Agur son of Jakeh, from Massa). The genealogical connection of Ishmael&#8217;s descendants to the wisdom literature&#8217;s fringe figures is a canonical-context note. The wisdom tradition reaches beyond Israel&#8217;s borders; Job is from Uz (Job 1:1, connected to Esau&#8217;s line), Agur is from Massa. The Spirit who gives wisdom does not respect the covenant boundaries in the same way that the specific covenant blessing does; wisdom literature is open to the wider ANE world.</p>",
"15": "<p>Hadad, Tema, Jetur, Naphish and Kedemah &#8212; the remaining sons of Ishmael, completing the twelve. Tema appears in Job 6:19 and Isaiah 21:14 as a desert caravan site. The desert peoples descended from Ishmael are part of the Pauline vision of Galatians: the Ishmael line represents the covenant of law that produces slavery (Gal 4:25), but the nations descended from Ishmael are not beyond the reach of the gospel. Paul&#8217;s Arabia (Gal 1:17: &#8220;I went into Arabia&#8221;) is Ishmael&#8217;s territory. The very land associated with the non-covenant son becomes the place of Paul&#8217;s early preparation for his Gentile mission.</p>",
"16": "<p>These were the sons of Ishmael; these are the names of the twelve tribal rulers according to their settlements and camps &#8212; twelve rulers from the non-covenant line, mirroring the structure of the covenant line (12 sons of Jacob). The parallel twelve-ruler structure across the covenant and non-covenant lines shows that God&#8217;s common ordering of peoples extends beyond the specific covenant community. The twelve-fold structure is God&#8217;s pattern for ordered community; in the new covenant, Christ reconstitutes it through twelve apostles who will &#8220;sit on twelve thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel&#8221; (Matt 19:28; Rev 21:14).</p>",
"17": "<p>Ishmael lived a hundred and thirty-seven years. He breathed his last and died, and was gathered to his people &#8212; Ishmael&#8217;s death at 137 is recorded with the same &#8220;gathered to his people&#8221; formula as Abraham (v8). The dignity of the same death-language for the non-covenant son demonstrates God&#8217;s care for Ishmael beyond the specific covenant. Christ&#8217;s death conquers death for all: &#8220;as in Adam all die, so in Christ all will be made alive&#8221; (1 Cor 15:22). The resurrection hope that Christ secures is not limited to the covenant line; the God who sees Ishmael (16:13) does not forget him in death.</p>",
"18": "<p>His descendants settled in the area from Havilah to Shur, near Egypt, toward Assyria &#8212; the settlement territory of Ishmael&#8217;s descendants corresponds roughly to the Arabian peninsula. The geographic scope of Ishmael&#8217;s inheritance &#8212; vast but not the promised land &#8212; is the type of the distinction between God&#8217;s general gifts to all peoples and his specific covenant inheritance secured through Christ. The nations have their appointed territories (Acts 17:26: &#8220;From one man he made all the nations&#8230; and he marked out their appointed times in history and the boundaries of their lands&#8221;); the covenant inheritance transcends national territories and is secured through Christ for all who believe.</p>",
"19": "<p>This is the account of Abraham&#8217;s son Isaac. Abraham became the father of Isaac &#8212; the new toledoth begins: the Isaac narrative. The double statement &#8220;Abraham&#8217;s son Isaac &#8212; Abraham became the father of Isaac&#8221; is deliberate: it asserts the covenant lineage explicitly after the long Ishmael genealogy. The covenant does not drift; it returns to the named channel. Matthew&#8217;s genealogy opens with the same insistence on lineage: &#8220;This is the genealogy of Jesus the Messiah the son of David, the son of Abraham&#8221; (Matt 1:1). The covenant chain &#8212; Abraham to Isaac to Jacob to&#8230; to David to&#8230; to Christ &#8212; is the backbone of salvation history.</p>",
"20": "<p>Isaac was forty years old when he married Rebekah daughter of Bethuel the Aramean &#8212; the covenant-heir&#8217;s marriage to Rebekah continues the covenant line. The emphasis on Rebekah&#8217;s Aramean origin (from Abraham&#8217;s extended family, not from Canaan) maintains the covenant community&#8217;s genealogical integrity. The great length devoted to finding Rebekah in ch24 signals that the continuation of the covenant line through the right wife is theologically significant. Christ himself comes from the covenant community (&#8220;descended from David according to the flesh,&#8221; Rom 1:3) &#8212; the incarnation is not a random entry into humanity but a specific genealogical embodiment of the covenant promise.</p>",
"21": "<p>Isaac prayed to the LORD on behalf of his wife, because she was childless. The LORD answered his prayer, and Rebekah became pregnant &#8212; the barren-wife-and-prayer pattern: Sarah (16:1&#8211;2; 21:1&#8211;2), Rebekah (here), Rachel (30:22), Hannah (1 Sam 1:19&#8211;20), Elizabeth (Luke 1:13). In each case, the covenant-bearing woman&#8217;s barrenness is answered by divine action in response to prayer, not by human effort. The sequence of barren women whose wombs God opens culminates in the supreme opening: the virgin Mary conceives by the Holy Spirit (Luke 1:35), bypassing not just infertility but marriage entirely. &#8220;Nothing will be impossible with God&#8221; (Luke 1:37) is spoken in direct allusion to Sarah&#8217;s case (18:14) and applies to all the barren-womb promises fulfilled in the one Christ.</p>",
"22": "<p>The babies jostled each other within her, and she said, &#8220;Why is this happening to me?&#8221; So she went to inquire of the LORD &#8212; the prenatal struggle within Rebekah is the starting point of the Jacob-Esau conflict that spans Genesis and beyond. The God who speaks into the prenatal situation is the God who knows persons before their birth: &#8220;Before I formed you in the womb I knew you, before you were born I set you apart&#8221; (Jer 1:5). Christ, in John 17:24, says the Father loved him &#8220;before the creation of the world.&#8221; The prenatal divine knowledge of Jacob and Esau is the OT expression of the pre-temporal divine knowledge of persons that the NT applies to both Christ and believers (Eph 1:4: &#8220;chosen in him before the creation of the world&#8221;).</p>",
"23": "<p>The LORD said, &#8220;Two nations are in your womb&#8230; one people will be stronger than the other, and the older will serve the younger&#8221; &#8212; Paul&#8217;s key election text in Rom 9:10&#8211;12: &#8220;Yet, before the twins were born or had done anything good or bad &#8212; in order that God&#8217;s purpose in election might stand: not by works but by him who calls &#8212; she was told, &#8216;The older will serve the younger.&#8217;&#8221; Paul uses this to demonstrate that God&#8217;s election precedes and is independent of human moral performance. The same principle applies to Christ: &#8220;chosen before the creation of the world&#8221; (1 Pet 1:20); &#8220;a chosen and precious cornerstone&#8221; (1 Pet 2:6 citing Isa 28:16). The God who chooses before birth is the God who chose Christ before creation and who chooses his people in Christ before the foundation of the world (Eph 1:4).</p>",
"24": "<p>When the time came for her to give birth, there were twin boys in her womb &#8212; the fulfillment of the prophesied twins confirms the divine word of v23. The &#8220;when the time came&#8221; formula marks the fulfillment of a divine promise within ordinary time &#8212; the same formula as Paul&#8217;s &#8220;when the set time had fully come, God sent his Son&#8221; (Gal 4:4). The birth of the promised child within ordinary time is the pattern of the incarnation: Christ is not a timeless myth but a historical birth &#8220;in the fullness of time,&#8221; within the flow of ordinary days and months and years. The twin birth fulfills what was announced before birth; the incarnation fulfills what was announced in the garden (Gen 3:15) and to Abraham (22:18).</p>",
"25": "<p>The first to come out was red, and his whole body was like a hairy garment; so they named him Esau &#8212; Esau&#8217;s red and hairy appearance gives him his name and his later alternate name Edom (&#8220;red,&#8221; v30). Edom becomes the persistent adversary of Israel throughout the prophets (Isa 34; 63; Obadiah) and the type of the world-power hostile to God&#8217;s people. The book of Revelation uses Edom imagery (Isa 63:1&#8211;6) for the rider on the white horse whose robe is dipped in blood (Rev 19:13). The figure of Esau/Edom runs from this red appearance in the womb through the OT&#8217;s prophetic condemnations to the apocalyptic victory of the Messiah over all adversaries.</p>",
"26": "<p>After this, his brother came out, with his hand grasping Esau&#8217;s heel; so he was named Jacob &#8212; Jacob grasping the heel at birth (&#8220;Jacob&#8221; = supplanter / he grasps the heel). Gen 3:15 promises enmity between the serpent&#8217;s offspring and the woman&#8217;s offspring, with the serpent striking the heel. Jacob&#8217;s heel-grasping from birth is the first heel reference after 3:15 and connects the Jacob narrative to the protoevangelium&#8217;s heel-enemy theme. Hosea 12:3 says Jacob &#8220;grasped his brother&#8217;s heel in the womb.&#8221; The struggle from birth is the type of the cosmic struggle between the seed of the woman and the seed of the serpent that Christ resolves by crushing the serpent&#8217;s head (Rom 16:20: &#8220;the God of peace will soon crush Satan under your feet&#8221;).</p>",
"27": "<p>The boys grew up, and Esau became a skillful hunter, a man of the open country, while Jacob was content to stay at home among the tents &#8212; the contrasting characters of the two sons. The tent-dwelling Jacob mirrors the earlier tent-dwelling of the covenant-bearers (12:8; 18:1; 25:3). The tent is the sign of the pilgrim who does not put down permanent roots in the current world but awaits the city whose foundations God has laid (Heb 11:9&#8211;10). Christ himself had no permanent home (Luke 9:58) and calls his disciples into the same pilgrim posture (John 17:16: &#8220;they are not of the world, even as I am not of it&#8221;). The tent-dweller lives by promise rather than by possession.</p>",
"28": "<p>Isaac, who had a taste for wild game, loved Esau, but Rebekah loved Jacob &#8212; the divided parental loyalty creates the family dysfunction that drives the next several chapters. The parental favoritism that distorts covenant family life is the background against which God&#8217;s impartial election operates: God chooses Jacob not because Rebekah prefers him but because of divine calling (Rom 9:11). The human distortions of love &#8212; favoritism, conditional affection &#8212; are the foil against which Christ&#8217;s love is defined: &#8220;God demonstrates his own love for us in this: While we were still sinners, Christ died for us&#8221; (Rom 5:8). Not conditional on our merit or others&#8217; preference, but unconditional in Christ.</p>",
"29": "<p>Once when Jacob was cooking some stew, Esau came in from the open country, famished &#8212; the scene of Esau&#8217;s fatigue and hunger is the setting for the most consequential bad decision in the patriarchal narrative. The physical hunger that drives Esau to trade his birthright is the type of the momentary desire that the NT warns against: &#8220;But each person is tempted when they are dragged away by their own evil desire and enticed. Then, after desire has conceived, it gives birth to sin; and sin, when it is full-grown, gives birth to death&#8221; (Jas 1:14&#8211;15). The hunger that feels like death (&#8220;I am about to die,&#8221; v32) overcomes the covenant sense; Christ&#8217;s response to hunger in the wilderness is the opposite: &#8220;Man shall not live on bread alone&#8221; (Matt 4:4).</p>",
"30": "<p>&#8220;Quick, let me have some of that red stew! I&#8217;m famished!&#8221; That is why he was also called Edom &#8212; Esau&#8217;s demand and nickname. The naming of Esau as Edom (&#8220;red&#8221;) in connection with the red stew is an etiological link between the individual and the nation. The Edomite nation that springs from Esau will be characterized by the same preference for immediate tangible benefit over long-term covenant inheritance. The prophetic condemnations of Edom (Oba 1; Jer 49:7&#8211;22; Ezek 25:12&#8211;14) see in Edom the continuation of Esau&#8217;s original disposition: the world-orientation that prefers what is seen over what is promised.</p>",
"31": "<p>Jacob replied, &#8220;First sell me your birthright&#8221; &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s shrewdness in recognizing the opportunity and the birthright&#8217;s value is itself a morally ambiguous act &#8212; exploiting his brother&#8217;s weakness. Yet the birthright comes to Jacob, which is what God declared before their birth (v23). The moral complexity of the covenant&#8217;s transmission through flawed human agents &#8212; Jacob is a supplanter, not a paragon of virtue &#8212; is the framework for understanding that God&#8217;s covenant purposes are not derailed by human moral failure. Christ does not come through a line of moral heroes but through a line of flawed people whose very failures make his righteousness stand out in greater relief (Matt 1:1&#8211;17 includes Tamar, Rahab, Ruth, and Bathsheba in the genealogy).</p>",
"32": "<p>Esau said, &#8220;Look, I am about to die. What good is the birthright to me?&#8221; &#8212; Esau&#8217;s dismissal of the birthright as worthless in the face of present hunger. Hebrews 12:16 names this as the defining characteristic: &#8220;godless like Esau, who for a single meal sold his inheritance rights as the oldest son.&#8221; The &#8220;I am about to die&#8221; exaggeration reveals a worldview that maximizes present comfort and discounts future inheritance. The gospel demands the opposite evaluation: &#8220;For I consider that the sufferings of this present time are not worth comparing with the glory that will be revealed in us&#8221; (Rom 8:18). The birthright &#8212; the covenant inheritance secured by Christ &#8212; is worth everything; trading it for any momentary satisfaction is the Esau mistake.</p>",
"33": "<p>Jacob said, &#8220;Swear to me first.&#8221; So he swore an oath to him, selling his birthright to Jacob &#8212; the oath formalizes the transaction. The covenant-oath pattern (swearing by God) is here used for an intra-family transaction that trades a divine inheritance for a bowl of stew. The degradation of the oath-covenant from the solemnity of the Abrahamic covenant (22:16: God swears by himself) to Esau&#8217;s casual oath over a meal represents the covenant&#8217;s devaluation by those who do not treasure it. Christ restores the weight and significance of the covenant through his own covenant-ratifying blood (Luke 22:20: &#8220;This cup is the new covenant in my blood&#8221;), the oath-covenant that cannot be traded or deprecated.</p>",
"34": "<p>Jacob gave Esau bread and lentil stew. He ate and drank, and then got up and left. So Esau despised his birthright &#8212; the summary verdict: Esau despised his birthright. The narrator does not soften the judgment. Heb 12:16&#8211;17 develops this: &#8220;Afterward, when he wanted to inherit this blessing, he was rejected. Even though he sought the blessing with tears, he could not change what he had done.&#8221; The irrevocability of the despising is the NT&#8217;s warning to those who treat lightly the covenant blessings of Christ: &#8220;How shall we escape if we ignore so great a salvation?&#8221; (Heb 2:3). The parable of the pearl of great price (Matt 13:45&#8211;46) presents the right response: the merchant &#8220;sold everything he had and bought it.&#8221; Esau is the antitype of the true wisdom that treasures the inheritance above all else.</p>",
},
"26": {
"1": "<p>There was a famine in the land, and Isaac went to Abimelech king of the Philistines at Gerar &#8212; the famine that sends Isaac toward Egypt (as it sent Abraham in 12:10) is the test of covenant loyalty. Will Isaac trust God&#8217;s provision in the land of promise, or seek security in Egypt? God intervenes (v2) before Isaac reaches Egypt. The temptation to seek security outside the covenant land &#8212; to go to Egypt in times of famine &#8212; runs through the OT as a type of trusting human powers over divine provision. Christ in the wilderness faces hunger and refuses to turn stones to bread (Matt 4:3&#8211;4), trusting divine provision rather than taking the self-providing route. The famine-to-foreign-land temptation and the covenant response are the type-and-antitype.</p>",
"2": "<p>The LORD appeared to Isaac and said, &#8220;Do not go down to Egypt; live in the land where I tell you to live&#8221; &#8212; the divine redirection before the covenant-bearer reaches Egypt. God&#8217;s word comes proactively, before the wrong decision is made, to keep Isaac within the covenant space. This proactive divine guidance is the pattern of the Spirit&#8217;s leading: &#8220;when he, the Spirit of truth, comes, he will guide you into all the truth&#8221; (John 16:13). Christ promises the Spirit as the guide who keeps believers from straying into the Egypt of spiritual compromise. The divine &#8220;do not go&#8221; is the shepherd&#8217;s voice that the sheep learn to follow (John 10:27: &#8220;my sheep listen to my voice; I know them, and they follow me&#8221;).</p>",
"3": "<p>&#8220;Stay in this land for a while, and I will be with you and will bless you. For to you and your descendants I will give all these lands, and I will confirm the oath I swore to your father Abraham&#8221; &#8212; the covenant confirmed to Isaac in all its original terms: presence (&#8220;I will be with you&#8221;), blessing, land, descendants, and oath-confirmation. The &#8220;I will be with you&#8221; formula runs through the OT as the supreme covenant assurance (to Jacob at Bethel, 28:15; to Moses, Exod 3:12; to Joshua, Josh 1:5) and culminates in Christ as Emmanuel (&#8220;God with us,&#8221; Matt 1:23). The promise &#8220;I will be with you&#8221; reaches its final expression in Matt 28:20: &#8220;I am with you always, to the very end of the age.&#8221;</p>",
"4": "<p>&#8220;I will make your descendants as numerous as the stars in the sky and will give them all these lands, and through your offspring all nations on earth will be blessed&#8221; &#8212; the Abrahamic promise repeated verbatim to Isaac. Paul cites &#8220;through your offspring all nations will be blessed&#8221; in Gal 3:8 as the gospel proclaimed in advance to Abraham &#8212; and this promise was renewed to Isaac. The same promise runs from Abraham through Isaac to Jacob to the covenant chain that reaches Christ. The phrase &#8220;through your offspring&#8221; is Paul&#8217;s key text for identifying the blessing-mediator as Christ: &#8220;The promises were spoken to Abraham and to his seed. Scripture does not say &#8216;and to seeds,&#8217;&#8230; but &#8216;and to your seed,&#8217; meaning one person, who is Christ&#8221; (Gal 3:16).</p>",
"5": "<p>&#8220;Because Abraham obeyed me and kept my requirements, my commands, my decrees and my instructions&#8221; &#8212; God cites Abraham&#8217;s obedience as the occasion for the covenant blessing to Isaac. Paul insists that this does not mean the covenant is earned by obedience: &#8220;The law, introduced 430 years later, does not set aside the covenant previously established by God and thus do away with the promise&#8221; (Gal 3:17). Abraham&#8217;s obedience is the response of faith, not the basis of election. Christ&#8217;s perfect obedience (Phil 2:8: &#8220;obedient to death &#8212; even death on a cross&#8221;; Rom 5:19: &#8220;through the obedience of the one man the many will be made righteous&#8221;) is the ultimate fulfillment of the obedience-blessing connection: Christ&#8217;s obedience secures the blessing for all who are in him.</p>",
"6": "<p>So Isaac stayed in Gerar &#8212; Isaac&#8217;s obedience to the divine word: he does not go to Egypt. The simple act of covenant obedience &#8212; staying in the promised land rather than seeking security elsewhere &#8212; is the type of the disciples&#8217; obedience: &#8220;do not leave Jerusalem, but wait for the gift my Father promised&#8221; (Acts 1:4). Staying in the place of divine appointment, trusting the divine provision, rather than seeking safety elsewhere, is the covenant posture. Christ himself stays on mission in Jerusalem despite the danger: &#8220;surely no prophet can die outside Jerusalem&#8221; (Luke 13:33). The covenant-bearer stays in the covenant place.</p>",
"7": "<p>When the men of that place asked him about his wife, he said, &#8220;She is my sister,&#8221; because he was afraid they would kill him on account of Rebekah &#8212; the third wife-sister deception in Genesis (after ch12 and ch20). The repetition of the identical failure across three generations &#8212; Abraham twice, Isaac once &#8212; establishes that the covenant-bearing patriarchs cannot secure the covenant promise by their own virtue. Each time, God must intervene to protect the woman through whom the covenant line will continue. The structural pattern of repeated human failure requiring divine intervention is the framework for the incarnation: where the covenant-bearers repeatedly failed to protect the promise, God sends his Son to accomplish what they could not (Rom 8:3: &#8220;what the law was powerless to do&#8230; God did by sending his own Son&#8221;).</p>",
"8": "<p>After a long time, Abimelech looked from a window and saw Isaac caressing his wife Rebekah &#8212; the deception is revealed through ordinary observation, not supernatural disclosure (unlike ch20 where God appeared in a dream). The truth emerges despite human concealment. Jesus&#8217;s teaching on the eventual revelation of hidden things applies: &#8220;There is nothing concealed that will not be disclosed, or hidden that will not be made known&#8221; (Luke 12:2). The covenant commitment that Isaac tried to hide &#8212; his marriage to Rebekah &#8212; is revealed by his own affection. The love that the covenant creates cannot ultimately be hidden; the gospel similarly cannot be permanently suppressed (Acts 5:39: &#8220;you will not be able to stop these men&#8221;).</p>",
"9": "<p>Abimelech summoned Isaac and said, &#8220;She is really your wife! Why did you say, &#8216;She is my sister&#8217;?&#8221; &#8212; the Gentile king again rebukes the covenant-bearer for moral failure (as in 20:9&#8211;10). The reversal &#8212; Gentile correcting Israelite &#8212; is the pattern Christ uses to challenge his own people: &#8220;I have not found such great faith even in Israel&#8221; (Matt 8:10); the Gentile centurion, the Samaritan leper, the Syrophoenician woman all display the faith that Israel&#8217;s covenant insiders lack. The light given to the covenant community is judged by what the outsiders see more clearly.</p>",
"10": "<p>Abimelech said, &#8220;What is this you have done to us? One of the men might well have slept with your wife, and you would have brought guilt upon us&#8221; &#8212; the guilt that the covenant-bearer&#8217;s deception would have brought upon the innocent Gentiles. The concept of collective guilt brought on an innocent community by the actions of a single individual is the shadow of the substitutionary atonement in reverse: Adam&#8217;s sin brings guilt upon all (Rom 5:12), but Christ&#8217;s righteousness brings justification to many (Rom 5:18&#8211;19). Here the guilt flows the wrong direction; the atonement redirects the flow so that Christ&#8217;s righteousness, not Isaac&#8217;s sin, determines the guilt-or-innocence of those connected to him.</p>",
"11": "<p>Abimelech gave orders: &#8220;Anyone who harms this man or his wife shall certainly be put to death&#8221; &#8212; the Gentile king protecting the covenant-bearer with royal authority. The protection of the covenant family by those outside the covenant is a recurring theme: Rahab protects the spies (Josh 2), Obadiah protects the prophets (1 Kgs 18:13), Cyrus permits the temple&#8217;s rebuilding (Ezra 1). God uses Gentile rulers to accomplish his covenant purposes. Christ is protected as an infant by the Magi&#8217;s warning to Herod and Joseph&#8217;s flight to Egypt (Matt 2:12&#8211;14); Pilate declares him innocent three times (John 18:38; 19:4, 6) even while condemning him. The protective declaration of Abimelech is the type of the providential protection God deploys through unlikely instruments.</p>",
"12": "<p>Isaac planted crops in that land and the same year reaped a hundredfold, because the LORD blessed him &#8212; the hundredfold harvest of Isaac in Philistia is the vocabulary of the parable of the sower: &#8220;Still other seed fell on good soil, where it produced a crop &#8212; a hundred, sixty or thirty times what was sown&#8221; (Matt 13:8). The hundredfold covenant blessing in enemy territory is the type of the gospel&#8217;s multiplication among the nations: &#8220;the word of God spread widely and grew in power&#8221; (Acts 19:20). The covenant-bearer&#8217;s hundredfold harvest in the land of the Philistines anticipates the gospel&#8217;s hundredfold multiplication among those who were not Israel (Rom 10:20: &#8220;I was found by those who did not seek me&#8221;).</p>",
"13": "<p>The man became rich, and his wealth continued to grow until he became very wealthy &#8212; the covenant-bearer prospers in the land of the Philistines. The prosperity of the righteous in foreign territory connects to Joseph in Egypt (39:2&#8211;6), Daniel in Babylon (Dan 1:17&#8211;20), and the church in the Roman Empire. The prosperity is not the point; the blessing that God channels through the covenant-bearer to the surrounding world is: &#8220;The LORD was with Joseph so that he prospered&#8230; his master saw that the LORD was with him&#8221; (Gen 39:2&#8211;3). Christ is the one in whom all the divine blessing is concentrated: &#8220;For God was pleased to have all his fullness dwell in him&#8221; (Col 1:19) &#8212; the supreme concentration of divine blessing in one person.</p>",
"14": "<p>He had so many flocks and herds and servants that the Philistines envied him &#8212; the Philistines&#8217; envy of Isaac&#8217;s blessing is a type of the world&#8217;s response to the covenant community&#8217;s prosperity: resentment rather than participation. The same dynamic occurs with Israel in Egypt (Exod 1:9&#8211;10: &#8220;the Israelites have become far too numerous for us&#8221;). The envy of the world at the covenant community&#8217;s blessing is one reason why the gospel encounters resistance: &#8220;if you belonged to the world, it would love you as its own. As it is, you do not belong to the world, but I have chosen you out of the world. That is why the world hates you&#8221; (John 15:19). The Philistines&#8217; envy anticipates the world&#8217;s hostility to Christ and his people.</p>",
"15": "<p>The Philistines had stopped up all the wells that Abraham&#8217;s servants had dug &#8212; the deliberate destruction of the water sources that Abraham&#8217;s servants had created. The stopping-up of wells is an act of covenant erasure: attempting to undo what the covenant-bearer established. The stopping of the wells corresponds to the religious powers&#8217; attempt to suppress the gospel: sealing the tomb (Matt 27:66), arresting the apostles (Acts 4:3; 5:18), scattering the church (Acts 8:1). But as Isaac re-opens the stopped wells (v18), Christ reopens what death closed: &#8220;I was dead, and now look, I am alive for ever and ever! And I hold the keys of death and Hades&#8221; (Rev 1:18).</p>",
"16": "<p>Abimelech said to Isaac, &#8220;Move away from us; you have become too powerful for us&#8221; &#8212; the expulsion of the covenant-bearer who has become too powerful for the surrounding culture. The pattern of expulsion from the surrounding culture runs from Isaac through Israel&#8217;s experience in Egypt (Exod 1:12: &#8220;the more they were oppressed, the more they multiplied and spread; so the Egyptians came to dread the Israelites&#8221;) to the church&#8217;s experience of Roman persecution and beyond. The covenant community&#8217;s growth provokes expulsion, but the expulsion cannot stop the growth. Christ is expelled from his hometown (Luke 4:29) and from Jerusalem at crucifixion; both expulsions become the catalyst for wider mission.</p>",
"17": "<p>So Isaac moved away and encamped in the Valley of Gerar, where he settled &#8212; Isaac&#8217;s patient relocation rather than confrontation. The willingness to yield territory rather than fight for it is Isaac&#8217;s characteristic response (see vv20&#8211;21). This patient yielding is the type of the meekness that inherits the earth: &#8220;Blessed are the meek, for they will inherit the earth&#8221; (Matt 5:5). Christ himself does not seize his kingdom by force but by submission and resurrection: &#8220;My kingdom is not of this world. If it were, my servants would fight&#8221; (John 18:36). The covenant inheritance comes through patience and trust, not through territorial aggression.</p>",
"18": "<p>Isaac reopened the wells that had been dug in the time of his father Abraham, which the Philistines had stopped up &#8212; the re-opening of Abraham&#8217;s wells is Isaac&#8217;s act of covenant continuity: honoring and continuing what his father began. The re-opening of stopped sources is the type of Christ restoring what sin has closed: access to God (Heb 10:19&#8211;22: &#8220;we have confidence to enter the Most Holy Place by the blood of Jesus&#8221;), the gift of the Spirit (Acts 2:17: &#8220;I will pour out my Spirit on all people&#8221; &#8212; the spiritual living water long stopped up by sin). Isaac gives the re-opened wells the same names his father had given them, maintaining covenant continuity; Christ fulfills rather than abolishes (Matt 5:17).</p>",
"19": "<p>Isaac&#8217;s servants dug in the valley and discovered a well of fresh water there &#8212; fresh (literally &#8220;living&#8221;) water discovered in the wilderness. &#8220;Living water&#8221; (mayim chayyim) is the OT&#8217;s image for both fresh flowing water and, symbolically, divine life and blessing (Jer 2:13: &#8220;they have forsaken me, the spring of living water&#8221;; 17:13; Zech 14:8). Christ applies the living-water image directly to himself (John 4:10&#8211;11; 7:38: &#8220;whoever believes in me&#8230; rivers of living water will flow from within them&#8221;). The discovery of living water in the valley is the type of the gospel&#8217;s discovery of the source of life in the most unexpected place &#8212; a crucified carpenter from Galilee.</p>",
"20": "<p>The herders of Gerar quarreled with Isaac&#8217;s herders, saying, &#8220;The water is ours!&#8221; So he named the well Esek, because they disputed with him &#8212; the first disputed well (Esek = contention). Isaac yields the well rather than fighting for it. The pattern of yield-to-peace is the gospel&#8217;s social ethics: &#8220;Do not repay anyone evil for evil&#8230; If it is possible, as far as it depends on you, live at peace with everyone&#8221; (Rom 12:17&#8211;18); &#8220;Do not take revenge&#8230; but leave room for God&#8217;s wrath&#8221; (Rom 12:19). Christ&#8217;s Sermon on the Mount develops this: &#8220;if someone takes your coat, do not withhold your shirt from them&#8221; (Luke 6:29). The first well yielded to contention is the type of the non-retaliatory posture that Christ commands.</p>",
"21": "<p>Then they dug another well, but they quarreled over that one too; so he named it Sitnah &#8212; the second disputed well (Sitnah = opposition, from the same root as &#8220;Satan&#8221; = adversary/accuser). The escalating opposition &#8212; from contention (Esek) to adversarial satanic opposition (Sitnah) &#8212; mirrors the escalating hostility the covenant community faces from generation to generation. Christ warns his disciples: &#8220;if they persecuted me, they will persecute you also&#8221; (John 15:20). The adversarial opposition of Sitnah is the type of the satanic opposition to the gospel (1 Thess 2:18: &#8220;Satan blocked our way&#8221;). Isaac&#8217;s response remains: yield and move on, trusting that God will provide room.</p>",
"22": "<p>He moved on from there and dug another well, and no one quarreled over it. He named it Rehoboth, saying, &#8220;Now the LORD has given us room and we will flourish in the land&#8221; &#8212; Rehoboth (room, spacious place) is the well of freedom and growth after the contested wells. The movement from contention (Esek) through adversarial opposition (Sitnah) to spaciousness (Rehoboth) is the arc of the covenant community through history &#8212; persecution, resistance, then divine vindication and room. Psalm 18:19: &#8220;He brought me out into a spacious place; he rescued me because he delighted in me.&#8221; Christ&#8217;s resurrection is the ultimate Rehoboth &#8212; the spacious place that opens after the contention and opposition of the cross: &#8220;death has been swallowed up in victory&#8221; (1 Cor 15:54).</p>",
"23": "<p>From there he went up to Beersheba &#8212; Isaac returns to the site of Abraham&#8217;s covenant-making (21:31&#8211;33). The return to Beer-sheba is a return to covenant ground, to the site of Abraham&#8217;s altar and worship. The covenant-bearer returns to the places of covenant worship when threatened by the surrounding world. The pattern of returning to covenant ground &#8212; to the altar, to prayer, to the place of divine encounter &#8212; under pressure is the shape of covenant faithfulness: &#8220;Draw near to God and he will draw near to you&#8221; (Jas 4:8). Christ returns to Jerusalem despite repeated threats (Luke 13:34&#8211;35) because it is the appointed covenant place of his sacrifice.</p>",
"24": "<p>That night the LORD appeared to Isaac and said, &#8220;I am the God of your father Abraham. Do not be afraid, for I am with you; I will bless you and will increase the number of your descendants&#8221; &#8212; the divine self-declaration &#8220;I am the God of your father Abraham&#8221; is the formula Jesus cites in the resurrection debate (Matt 22:32) to prove the resurrection: the God of Abraham is the God of the living. The &#8220;Do not be afraid, for I am with you&#8221; formula is the recurring divine assurance that runs through every major covenant appearance and reaches its fullest expression in Christ: &#8220;Do not be afraid. I am the First and the Last. I am the Living One; I was dead, and now look, I am alive for ever and ever!&#8221; (Rev 1:17&#8211;18). The &#8220;I am&#8221; of this verse is the same divine self-declaration that Christ claims in John 8:58.</p>",
"25": "<p>Isaac built an altar there and called on the name of the LORD. There he pitched his tent, and there his servants dug a well &#8212; the three covenant activities at Beer-sheba: altar (worship), tent (pilgrim dwelling), well (life-sustaining provision). The altar at Beer-sheba continues the Abrahamic pattern of building altars at each new covenant location (12:7&#8211;8; 13:18; 22:9). The altar&#8211;tent&#8211;well triad is the covenant community&#8217;s basic structure: worship, pilgrim dwelling, divine provision. Christ fulfills all three: he is the altar (Heb 13:10: &#8220;We have an altar from which those who minister at the tabernacle have no right to eat&#8221;), the dwelling place (John 1:14: &#8220;The Word became flesh and made his dwelling among us&#8221;), and the well (John 4:14).</p>",
"26": "<p>Meanwhile, Abimelech had come to Isaac from Gerar, with his adviser Ahuzzath and Phicol the commander of his forces &#8212; the same Abimelech and Phicol who made the covenant with Abraham (21:22, 32) come now to Isaac. The diplomatic continuity across generations confirms the long-term significance of the covenant family&#8217;s presence in Canaan. The nations come to the covenant-bearer, not the other way around &#8212; a type of the eschatological gathering: &#8220;All the nations you have made will come and worship before you, Lord&#8221; (Ps 86:9); the Magi coming to Bethlehem (Matt 2:1&#8211;2). The nations&#8217; approach to the covenant-bearer is the pattern of the gospel&#8217;s claim on all peoples.</p>",
"27": "<p>Isaac asked, &#8220;Why have you come to me, since you were hostile to me and sent me away?&#8221; &#8212; Isaac&#8217;s honest confrontation of the previous hostility before making peace. The confrontation of wrong before reconciliation is the pattern of the gospel&#8217;s message: the cross confronts the reality of human sin before offering forgiveness. Christ does not ignore the hostility that put him on the cross but absorbs and forgives it: &#8220;Father, forgive them, for they do not know what they are doing&#8221; (Luke 23:34). The reconciliation that follows honest confrontation &#8212; not denial &#8212; is the shape of the gospel&#8217;s peace-making.</p>",
"28": "<p>They answered, &#8220;We saw clearly that the LORD was with you; so we said there ought to be a sworn agreement between us. Let us make a treaty with you&#8221; &#8212; the Gentile nations seeking covenant because they see God&#8217;s presence with the covenant-bearer. The same logic drives Paul&#8217;s Gentile mission: &#8220;will not their full inclusion be life from the dead?&#8221; (Rom 11:15); Israel&#8217;s restoration will provoke Gentile envy and turning (Rom 11:11). The Philistines see God&#8217;s presence with Isaac and seek treaty; Gentiles see God&#8217;s presence in the church and are drawn to Christ. The visible divine presence with the covenant community is the missionary force that draws the nations (John 13:35: &#8220;all people will know that you are my disciples, if you love one another&#8221;).</p>",
"29": "<p>&#8220;That you will do us no harm&#8230; You are now the blessed of the LORD&#8221; &#8212; the nations&#8217; declaration: &#8220;you are the blessed of the LORD.&#8221; The covenant-bearer&#8217;s blessing is recognized by the surrounding nations as divine in origin. Paul in Gal 3:9 uses the blessing-of-the-nations language to identify the gospel: &#8220;those who rely on faith are blessed along with Abraham, the man of faith.&#8221; The Abimelech-Isaac covenant is a Gentile treaty with the blessed-of-the-LORD; the new covenant extends this: all who are in Christ are &#8220;blessed&#8230; with every spiritual blessing in the heavenly realms&#8221; (Eph 1:3), recognized by the spiritual powers as the blessed-of-the-Father.</p>",
"30": "<p>Isaac then made a feast for them, and they ate and drank &#8212; the covenant sealed by a shared meal. The covenant meal runs through the OT: Abraham and Melchizedek&#8217;s bread and wine (14:18), the covenant ratification at Sinai (Exod 24:11: &#8220;they saw God, and they ate and drank&#8221;), and reaches its fulfillment in the Lord&#8217;s Supper (Luke 22:15&#8211;20) and the eschatological feast (Rev 19:9: &#8220;Blessed are those who are invited to the wedding supper of the Lamb&#8221;). Isaac&#8217;s feast with Abimelech is a Gentile inclusion in the covenant meal &#8212; a type of the eschatological feast from which &#8220;many will come from east and west and will take their places at the feast with Abraham, Isaac and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven&#8221; (Matt 8:11).</p>",
"31": "<p>Early the next morning the men swore an oath to each other. Then Isaac sent them on their way, and they went away peacefully &#8212; the covenant sealed with an oath and confirmed by a peaceful departure. The peace-making that produces a peaceful departure is the model of the gospel&#8217;s social ethic: &#8220;make every effort to live in peace with everyone&#8221; (Heb 12:14). Christ&#8217;s resurrection sends the disciples out in peace: &#8220;Peace be with you&#8221; (John 20:19, 21, 26) &#8212; the risen Christ&#8217;s greeting is the peace of the accomplished covenant, not a provisional treaty like Isaac&#8217;s but the permanent peace of the new covenant ratified in Christ&#8217;s blood (Eph 2:14).</p>",
"32": "<p>That day Isaac&#8217;s servants came and told him about the well they had dug: &#8220;We&#8217;ve found water!&#8221; &#8212; the discovery of the well on the day of the Abimelech covenant is the divine confirmation of the covenant: the water of life arrives at the moment the covenant is sealed. The connection of water-discovery to covenant-making runs through the OT (Moses at the rock in Exod 17:6, the covenant at Sinai immediately after) and reaches its climax at Pentecost: the gift of the Spirit as living water (John 7:38&#8211;39; Acts 2:17) arrives when the new covenant community is established. The covenant sealed and the water found on the same day is the type of the Spirit given when the new covenant is inaugurated.</p>",
"33": "<p>He called the well Shibah (oath / seven), and to this day the name of the town has been Beersheba &#8212; Beersheba named again, this time by Isaac rather than Abraham (21:31). The re-naming of Beer-sheba by Isaac with the same meaning confirms the covenant continuity: the same God, the same oath, the same covenant-place across generations. The continuity of covenant-naming is the type of the unbroken covenant chain from Abraham to Isaac to Jacob to Christ. &#8220;Jesus Christ is the same yesterday and today and forever&#8221; (Heb 13:8) &#8212; the covenant-keeper whose name does not change across generations is the antitype of the oath that Beer-sheba commemorates.</p>",
"34": "<p>When Esau was forty years old, he married Judith daughter of Beeri the Hittite, and Basemath daughter of Elon the Hittite &#8212; Esau&#8217;s Hittite wives mark his departure from the covenant community&#8217;s endogamous marriage practice. Where Isaac was sent to Paddan Aram to find a covenant wife (24:3&#8211;4), Esau marries from the Canaanites without covenant concern. The marriage outside the covenant community is the type of the broader covenant faithlessness that the prophets condemn in Israel: &#8220;Do not be yoked together with unbelievers&#8221; (2 Cor 6:14). Esau&#8217;s marriages are the biographical expression of the birthright-despising disposition: covenant community and covenant inheritance are both secondary to present convenience.</p>",
"35": "<p>They were a source of grief to Isaac and Rebekah &#8212; Esau&#8217;s Hittite wives cause grief to his covenant parents. The grief of covenant parents at the covenant-indifference of a child is the emotional weight that drives the rest of the Isaac narrative: Rebekah will ensure that Jacob finds a proper covenant wife (27:46&#8211;28:2). The grief at covenant unfaithfulness reaches its depth in Christ&#8217;s lament over Jerusalem: &#8220;Jerusalem, Jerusalem, you who kill the prophets and stone those sent to you, how often I have longed to gather your children together, as a hen gathers her chicks under her wings, and you were not willing&#8221; (Matt 23:37). The covenant Lord&#8217;s grief at the covenant people&#8217;s rejection is the ultimate expression of the grief that Esau&#8217;s Hittite marriages anticipate.</p>",
},
}

